LINEAR STEADY STATE CONDUCTION IN 010 DIRECTION WITH HEX MESH

A basic heat conduction test in [0,1]^3 with a linear steady state solution
between fixed temperatures on opposing faces of the cube, with no-flux BC on
the other faces.  Here we are concerned with recovering the steady state
solution T = 1 + a*x + b*y + c*z, H = 2*T for a given direction abc, and not
not so much with the transient approach to steady state.

&MESH
  x_axis%coarse_grid = 0.0, 1.0
  x_axis%intervals   = 5
  y_axis%coarse_grid = 0.0, 1.0
  y_axis%intervals   = 5
  z_axis%coarse_grid = 0.0, 1.0
  z_axis%intervals   = 5
/

&OUTPUTS
  output_t = 0.0, 500.0
  output_dt = 500.0
/

&PHYSICS
  materials = 'stuff'
  heat_transport = .true.
/

&DIFFUSION_SOLVER
  abs_temp_tol       = 0.0
  rel_temp_tol       = 1.0e-4
  abs_enthalpy_tol   = 0.0
  rel_enthalpy_tol   = 1.0e-4
  nlk_tol            = 0.05
  nlk_preconditioner = 'hypre_amg'
  verbose_stepping   = .true.
/

&NUMERICS
  dt_init = 1.0d-5
  dt_min  = 1.0d-7
  dt_grow = 10.0
  dt_max  = 100.0
/

&THERMAL_BC
  name = 'left dirichlet'
  type = 'temperature'
  face_set_ids = 3
  temp = 1.0
/

&THERMAL_BC
  name = 'right dirichlet'
  type = 'temperature'
  face_set_ids = 4
  temp = 2.0
/

&THERMAL_BC
  name = 'symmetry planes'
  type = 'flux'
  face_set_ids = 1, 2, 5, 6
  flux = 0.0
/

&BODY
  surface_name = 'from mesh file'
  mesh_material_number = 1
  material_name = 'stuff'
  temperature = 1.0
/

&MATERIAL
  name = 'stuff'
  density = 4.0
  specific_heat = 0.5
  conductivity = 1.0
/
